\section{Audiovisual acquisition and processing}
\label{sec:acquisition}
The video and audio of the performance were acquired and preprocessed by Pavel \v{S}iler, Petr Holub\'{a}\v{r}, and students of the \acro{LEMMA} laboratory.~\cite{lemma} We normalized the video format and mixed ambient sound and Ji\v{r}\'{i} Zlatu\v{s}ka's opening speech into the audio.

\subsection{Video acquisition}
The video recording of the performance was made by Pavel \v{S}iler using a Sony~\acro{PXW-X70} camera. The footage includes Donald Knuth's lectures at \acro{FI~MU}, as well as shots of the church and organ and the opening speech by Ji\v{r}\'{i} Zlatu\v{s}ka.

\subsection{Video processing}
Although the video was acquired in a resolution of $1920\times1080$\,px at 25 frames per second (\acro{FPS}), the final recording was expected to have at least twice the resolution (\acro{4K}) and frame rate (50~\acro{FPS}).

The lecture recordings were provided in a non-interlaced format, whereas the footage of the church, organ, and opening speech was in an interlaced format. In addition, the lectures and opening speech were recorded from a tripod, in contrast to the handheld shots of the church and organ. The goal of the video processing was therefore not only to increase the resolution and frame rate, but also to unify the video format and stabilize the handheld footage.

\begin{figure*}[t]
\centering
